 „Éª„Éª„Éª 
 ùêäùêáùêàùêëùêÄ ùêÜùêÄùêàùêçùêìùêáùêÄ ùêÜùêéùêÉùêà

Made during Pausha Amabasya, this delicacy is an age old tradition in Odia culture. Many people make it for Manabasa Gurubar as a prasad to Godess Laxmi. 
KHIRA in odiya means milk, GAINTHA means dumplings and GODI is stones as the rice dumplings look like small stones. 
It's an amazing recipe with a mild sweetness and the flavour of tender coconut. 
As we r getting busy in our day to day life we r slowly moving away from our traditions. To be honest even my family has stopped making these recipes as they are time taking and we don't have time. 
I have revived this recipe with my own alterations but I have kept the base intact so that it doesn't loose its essence. 
Thank you so much @chiragprasanna for helping me putting this up. Without u it wouldn't have been possible.
